annotation: This looks like a normal Slav defense except that black hasn't played Nf6 yet.
This capture doesn't help black at all.
Repeatedly I have seen that when black tries to hang onto the c4 pawn it backfires badly for him.

This is the wrong move order for the subtle reason that if White plays first axb5 cxb5 b3 and now Qa5+ is met with Nd2 and now c3 allows Qf3 with the attack on the rook on a8.  This is not possible if white doesn't play axb5 first!
This is the wrong choice as it gives White a huge advantage.  Instead Qa5+ Qd2 (or b4 Qd8) c3 Qc2 is nearly equal for Black.
Where is the weakness in black's position?
Bd6 would have been a much better choice.
It would have been better to play Qc7 because of the tactical trick after Nxe7 Ng4 threatening mate f4 Kxe7 and now the black king has an escape square.
Not as good as Nxe7 Kxe7 Ba3+ Ke8 Rfc1 according to my computer.
Black could have played Nd5 and is king would have a better chance at castling or escaping to f6 if white makes both captures on e7.
Here black blunders but it would be useful to look what would happen after Ng8 (Nd5 e4) Ne5! Ngf6 Rfc1 and the queen has nowhere to hide if Qd8 then  Nc6 and black loses his queen or gets mated.

I played as black in this game. I'm still trying to learn the basics of the Kings Indian and won this game because of sheer luck. Of course I'd rather not like to win this way and would like any input you guys can give.
A flexible response. I can still go d5 and transpose if I wish as well as do many other things.
I'm not grabbing the center so he is.
Preparing Bg7.
Here he can't play e5 because after the exchanges his knight will have had to move backward losing time.
I debated Bg4 here. However White could just kick it away with h3 since Bh5 loses the Bishop.
This seemed more natural to me.
I would say Bd3 is better but my f7 g6 h7 pawn formation seems to make that less appealing. The LSB for white seems a bit useless for the time being.
While it looks like this loses a pawn I don't think it does because after dxe5 dxe5 Nxe5 Nxe4! With a discovered attack on the e5 Knight.
This came as a shock to me. I think the best move here would have just been to move the rook seeing what happened.
Instead I developed another piece which seems fine.
And now he's threatening Nxe5 since my knight on d7 is pinned.
I thought this fixed the problem but it invites whites next move.
I didn't see this move and it benefits white in the end.
I didn't want to let him have my more active rook.
This will at least slow him down a little.
My only chance here was to try and push the e pawn. Sadly I think this position is probably lost for black at this point with proper play.
A better move here I thought was Ne6 gaining the Bishop pair. Also his extended Knight could be a liability.
After doing the calculations white doesn't win a pawn here after Bishop takes.
Now if Rxc5 I hav Bf8. and if Rc6 I have Bb7 winning a piece.
Forced.
With looks at Ne4 and Nb3. Both look very good attacking the c5 pawn.
Giving new life to the DSB. This bishop is going to be my savior since it can't be challenged easily.
Getting out of the pin.
I need to move as quick as possible.
And the pawn will hold at least for now.
I didn't plan on taking with Bxh2 here. I don't want that c pawn to become passed. Also white will have too much activity after Nxc5.
He played this anyway. I guess he didn't like the tactics or something.
Covering the e6 Square so my LSB can move.
Threatens Nxa7 and Nd6+
I'm down 3 points now... and he has a passed pawn too.
This was probably the main reason I won. One blunder can cost the game some times.
He still is up a pawn but I have too much activity now.

He resigned here. Let me know what you guys think and give me lots of pointers! :D Oh and if anyone wants to play me as white and play the kings Indian rated or unrated message me or challenge me and I'll play. It has to be the Kings Indian though! lol

Personally I prefer 3. Bb5 for more of a Ruy Lopez approach but this is a good alternative and accomplishes the same goal: develops the piece and prepares for castle. As Hicks points out and as I tell my over-the-board students: the best opening moves accomplish multiple goals!

The Giuoco Piano in which the goals are for white:  to take control of the center with a d4 push. White must choose if he does it right now--4. d4 to get a lead in development (despite the loss of the pawn)--or if he prepares it with moves like 4. c3 or 4. b4. White may also forget about the d4-push and play a quieter line by supporting the center with 4. d3. But these are too conventional for white's tastes...
!? - Instead white elects to go for an Evans Gambit in which the goal is to trade a pawn for better center position.
Black takes as most people who see this line do. After all even the original annotator says the best way to refute a gambit is to accept the offer.
Played to keep pressure on c3. After d4(?) c3 is pinned
3rd goal of the chess opening? Protect the king! This standard move fixes the pin problem and makes d4 a playable move again.
!? - A good move since the pawn on c3 makes e4 difficult to defend and ideally would allow black to castle as well...

However as many people will tell you offense is the best defense. Ignoring the attack on e4 white invites black to take it knowing that this opens the e-file for the white rook giving him a positional edge! This move also prevents black from castling which will become a problem later in the game.
Attacks d4 as black looks to prepare for an attack on the center.
Develops the queen and attacks f7!
?! - a dubious move as black's king hasn't castled yet and is stuck in the middle. On the flip side there is not much else he can do to defend f7. Bad positions force bad moves.
Opens the e-file for the rook to attack the king! Time to make black pay for not castling.
Black's plan? Trade and simplify. It's really his only hope.
Quiz for you spectators: Why isn't Kd7 an option here? (Hint: The move made is the only good move for black!)
!! - a beautiful queen sacrifice.
An exposed king = no es bueno for anyone.
Time for white to make the most of the queen sacrifice. One bad move and black can sneak back into the game.
A beautiful finish! Lesson of this game: Castle! And if your opponent doesn't look for and capitalize on the weak square f7 (and/or f2).
here white could not to take but he choose to capture
this move actually sets up a trap which my opponent bit on
here black has a nic move available to atleast gain back the pawn
Ngxe5!
and my opponent took the bishop but missed blacks lethatl blow
hope you enjoyed:)
My traditional opening.
I normally play my bishop at this point. 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 xc6 5. Nxe5 f6 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. O-O is what I usually experience or something along those lines. I didn't do it here this time.
Getting my knights out.
Apparently so is he.
Preparing to castle.
He is as well.
I didn't want my pawn structure to be messed up or unbalanced so I got the other bishop involved.
Now I can castle.
Defenses are good but I apply that for both sides.
He does the same strategy he just did with my other knight.
My bishop is already placed.
Knights can be lethal so I wasn't gonna let that one get in any deeper.
In my opinion knights are stronger than bishops.
The game is evenly matched so far.
I hope to gain a pawn.
An expected move.
Now I gain an advantage. He could take my pawn but then his rook would be gone but not taking the pawn results in losing the knight.
He makes the smart move.
I have a good advantage now.
I'm hoping to trade rooks.
According to plan...
...but my original plan was to let him attack...
...but he was so insistent I did the honors lol
But it wasn't the best idea. His b5 pawn is now open for attack.
My advantage grows.
My advantage grows further. He doing his best for sure but he's letting his pawns drop off.
Of course removing the pawns allowed him to attack my queen but we all know I won't let him get it.
A bit surprised he didn't try to defend his a5 pawn.
I go another pawn up my advantage is big! I'm a bit surprised with how he let them go.
I still need that rook.
Really a forced move. Moving the queen to protect would of resulted in disaster for me.
Hoping to exchange the last two rooks.
All according to plan.
I failed to see that coming though.
My advantage is smaller now but now I would make it tough for dfb1 by engaging my a and c pawns.
Not much else he could do.
Again not much else he could do.
This allowed me though to drive back whatever he was planning.
The fg and h pawns on both sides are basically stalemated right now.
Black's lonesome queen can't stop both pawns.
Nothing else black could do.

This sequence of moves was likely to occur next: 40. Ke7 41. c7 Kd7 42. c8=Q+ Qxc8 43. Qxc8+ Kxc8 44. a8=Q+... I probably would of attacked black's f g and h pawns so I could engage my f g and h pawns so I could get more strong pieces to make checkmate easier. Checkmate is hard to do right now. dfb1 though knew that he would lose his queen and that I would still have a queen and so on. He resigned and this wonderful game was over. I hope you enjoyed this annotation and feel free to comment and rate this annotation.

This was one of my first and probably the shortest game I have played (so far) in the Walking the Walk & Learning to Run Welcome MT 11

I think it can best be described as a painful reminder of what can go wrong in a game
Tournament starting position
At this point I was reasonably happy that white had a weakened pawn structure and I would soon be able to castle
This is one of those moves that at the time I thought was fairly innocuous however it is anything but.

This is where we vary from the Gameknot database which only has h4 as an option. Although I was suspicious of this as an unusual move I couldn't see what was to come. In fact this move serves two purposes firstly it keeps the d1 h5 diagonal clear for the queen and secondly it threatens the rather nasty Ng5
simple developing move to threaten the pawn on e5
This was a bolt from the blue for me. My first instinct was not to take it however after Qh5 I would be in serious trouble
Pretty much the only way to avoid mate if I can get my king on f8 it can at least get a little protection from the knight which can go to g8
Of course white isn't going to allow me that luxury
with hindsight I realised the purpose of this was to open the a3-f8 diagonal for whites dsb
This achieves nothing other than losing material as we will see

At this point I'd had more than enough as mate is imminent. 

Thanks for reading please comment.
All the games start here. White has sacrificed a Knight to expose Black's King.
I open more lines and now threaten to bring my QB into the attack as well.
Black defends the KNP and opens a line for his B to participate in the defense.
I follow up by developing the B with a capture.
Black immediately counters by threatening the B.
I guard it.
Black attacks it again but leaves himself open...
...to this Pawn fork.
The "desperado" B captures a Pawn...
...before dying.
Black brings his Knight to the center.
My most powerful piece joins the attack. The Black Knight is a goner.
A mistake. Down in material Black's strategy should be to keep the Q's on the board and seek complications.
15... N-B3 saves the Rook.
Now it must fall.
Now it's a matter of mopping up.
I activate my other Rook.
Every exchange helps me.
Eliminating Black's resistance.
Black resigns as he has no way to avoid having his Rook be exchanged off.

?
Sacrificing a tempo this early to play d5 seems strange - especially given that white is almost always able to play d5 later in the Dutch...perhaps my opponent doesn't know the typical lines?

? 
Another pawn move to reinforce d5 but why c4 instead of Nf3 or g3?
Leningrad variation

?
Again this pattern of pawn moves aiming at the light squares but f3 hinders the knight and allows me to develop as normal without trouble.
It's ugly but he has to develop and the knight is otherwise trapped at home.

*
I'm not sure about this move - it's obvious that I was afraid of Ng5 (which has hurt me more than once in the Dutch) - and h6 definitely keeps the knight on an irrelevant square but it also weakens my king and does not develop anything. Maybe Qe8 Bd7 or even Na6 would have been better? Tough call. This may have been a great move - it may have also just expressed undue terror.

?
Maybe I'm missing something but why switch the focus from e6 to e5 - Nf4 brings back in the horse that this pawn kept out - why block it with the same pawn AND lose tempo?

!
Punish sub par moves quickly

? 
Just an error

?
I chose not to trade queens here (perhaps an error) but trading queens while material down is usually a mistake.

?
Giving up tempo - it's better to move forward than look back!

? 
A cute idea but easy to defend - I'm material up; it's time to be violent  not play for some subtle infiltration maneuver. Just triple on the d file and krush (like Irina!)

!
The first of many tempo losses Qa5 cost me. No me gusta.
After all of that I get a pawn my queen is on a shitty square and I'm no closer to mobilizing my material advantage and killing the king.

!
Yes Ali babe - get the king!!!
Oh NOW you want to trade queens - 39000 moves after you should have.

?
This just seems bad. I feel like he should march pawns or build a battery. A better player could have exploited this.

?
Now I'm giving back all of my material. Are you trying to draw Ali?

?
Angling for a mate that isn't there - cut your losses and defend what material you still have!
He just wants to draw - and he does!
The rest of the game is inconsequential - we wander the board....I make some dumb mistakes  there's a big mate attempt that ends in a stupid blunder and frustrated I repeat on move 60 and draw.

Final thought - trade queens when you're up; don't be subtle you'll lose the initiative  and for fuck's sake don't sac everything for a mate after it's too late. Be aggressive while you can be not after the time has passed.
My 2nd learning game with darknite13 in the Walking the Walk and Learning to Run chess club.
Black responds with the Sicilian Defence.
The last move from the games database - the real challenge starts here!
Priority is to get the King to safety.
Here I am targetting the seemingly unprotected pawn on d6 with my knight and queen....I just need to try to shift the black knight on d4 by pushing the c pawn.

Plan didn't work as I can't take the black d pawn with my Queen!  But I'm happy to exchange pieces instead.  I'm also very pleased to have a Bishop and Knight in exchange for 2 Knights.  I believe Bishops become slightly better as the game progresses.
Move bishop to safety but I have left my b pawn in danger. I decided to protect e4 pawn as this controls the center.
This move really surprised me I didn't understand it.  I could only think that black decided to maintain his pawn structure around his king should I have taken the Knight on my next move.
I was given the opportunity to protect my b pawn - I was happy as my pieces seemed safe plus I had some control of various squares with my queen and bishops
I thought my Bishop on g5 looked inactive so I decided to pull it back to e3 where it appears to control more squares.

I had an option here to take the knight however I prefer bishops over knights so decline the exchange and add extra protection to my e4 pawn.  I liked this move as it also gives my white square bishop extra mobility - as up to now it has been wasted guarding a single pawn.
I was really confused here...the fact black offered the pawn exchange made me suspect that he had an unpleasant surprise in store so I decline  and try to bring my Queen in to the game.
I am feeling squeezed!

Not much choice really.  I considered Bishop to g5 however I was concerned the bishop might end up becoming trapped by a pawn push and I don't want to use the safety net around my King just yet just to defend a bishop.  But....I was mistaken the bishop would have had an easy exit on the h4 diagonal....I failed to spot ths at the time.
Black pulls out a tank - the game is heating up
Trying to apply pressure to the weaker of the 2 pawns
Here I apply a double attack on the e5 pawn whilst moving my queen to safety.  I was considering pawn to f4 next.

Regrettably I am forced to pull my queen out of the game and my previous moves assisted black in making a strong pawn structure.  My pieces are becoming closed in all because I let black control the centre with his pawns.
....ouch...I left e3 completely open!
Rf2 to provide extra protection to c2 and g2.

Black owns the c line however I'm not seeing anything too dangerous at this stage.  I think c2 is well protected and I plan to keep my white square bishop and one other defender (such as the Queen or Rook on f2) exactly where they are.
Change of strategy - time to try and break up the pawn structure.
Here I am considering exchanging my rook for the knight and pawn.  This will leave me a point down however I don't like the knight so far forward attacking important squares around my king.
That is unpleasant as I don't like the idea of black controlling the f file should I take the knight on e3 with my rook.
So I take the rook I think it was right to try to take away blacks control of both the c and f files particularly as that rook may have potentially blocked 2 escape squares for my king.
So black regains control of the f file but at least now the c file is free but I still have a problem with that black knight.
Second attempt at attacking the knight!
Bring bishop to safety and an attempt to block the black queen from moving to e7 and possibly followed up by f7.
A 3rd attempt at attacking the knight in that undesirable position!

Arrggg....at last I get that knight!! I thought taking the bishop would leave my king wide open.

I had to carefully calculate though the threat to my King.  The Queen can easily move to g6 and the rook is controlling the f file.  I decide I can protect my g pawn with my bishop to f1.
Defending against mate.

Spent ages on this move it looked safe to take the pawn. Additionally I attack the bishop and make my queen active again.

Both my pawn on g2 and bishop on f1 are protected.

Seemed so natural to take with the rook here....and then bang!! Game over - this was what I analysed before this move!  At this point I noticed that I must take with the king and bring it to a safe square.  I am very fortunate to have an escape route.
The lucky escape!
Lose my rook but happy to take the bishop - I am having a massive amount of luck here!
Here I know that exchanging queens is a losing move.  I thought about king to c1 then I lose the e or a pawns and I couldn't see any counter play.
Here I resign as I can't think of how I can stop black from promoting a pawn.
So like me he starts off with the most common opening.
Standard.
Also standard.

?! I understand this move in the sense that it develops since black just advanced his other center pawn.  However this is inaccurate and better was 2...d5 as after 3.exd5 Qxd5  This move however compromises space for his DSB so that he'll either have to cram it or waste time to get it out.
So white decides to take advantage of that with this move.  The idea behind it is to keep that B crammed by exchanging and that's about to happen.
So black decides to bring another piece out.
Of course white decides to pin that N and that's something that I also would have done.

Very understandable and it is a good way to get out of it.  And instead of retreating on h4 followed by g3 chicoboy is going to exchange his DSB for black's N.  However I would've liked 5...Bf7 and it's the most common way to break the pin.  Jack Stockel told me that both ways wheather the opponent develops his B or brings out his P like this are both equally common.  But what I especially like about 5...Bf7 is that it would have developed another piece whereas this is not a developing move.

In this position white thought that his N was in danger and this move does protect it.  However Gerhard's d N was not in danger because of his Q.  In my mind better was 7.Nc3.  The problem with this move is that it doesn't develop anything and in fact takes away a square that would normally be used to get the b1 Knight out.  In addition this makes it less safe for white to castle K side.

And now black is trying to find a weakness with this move.  I figured it out the reason that I've been into attacking material all has to do with tempo gain and this is exactly what this move does.  As IM elyhim put it "Gaining tempo is like taking money out of your opponents and depositing it in your own bank."  Well that is the case here because once white retreats black will be able to develop another piece.

As noted earlier because black played 2...d6 as opposed to 2...d5 this is the consequence.  While it might appear that having a crammed bishop isn't a problem it's actually quite serious because it will make it very difficult to near impossible for black to control the center given that the center is not well coordinated for black.

So although slightly crammed it's less then black and this move actually gives white an advantage all of a sudden.  Now both players are equal in terms of development but white's center is better coordinated and should be able to control within the next few moves.
So black now decides to pin white's N.
As noted and implied earlier I would have played 10.Be2 instead.

This time however no exchange.  Instead black retreats but I'm not crazy about this at all.  Instead I would've exchanged because once white reattacks with 11.g4 black has to retreat again after which white can finally complete develop after 12.Bb5+.
But black's also completely developed.  The only difference as noted earlier however is that white's center is controlled whereas black is not so chicoboy has a noticeable edge at this point.
And now white's remaining piece out.  The only thing left is for him to castle.
And that however is something that black does.
I don't know why white played this because his LSB is not attacked.

?! The goal here is for black to put pressure on the e file.  However in my opinion this move is an inaccuracy because Jack Stockel told that it's generally a bad idea to bring both of your R's on the same file.

!? Yes white does castle but in my mind this is not his best move.  In fact it's risky because in general with this position being a perfect a example castling Q side often leaves your K vulnerable to exposure and this is a well known fact.  Therefore castling K side so 15.0-0 was best in my mind.
I don't know why black played this.
I'm not sure what this move accomplishes.
At this point black intends to exchange white's B for his N.  Not exactly sure why because in this position a N is worth more then a B.
But white is not going to allow that.  However I would've exchanged because that would have immediately created a weakness.
Putting pressure on the b file.

? Now white is going for an exchange.  At this point black better be careful because his Q is left en-prise.  And if he doesn't find the right move white will win for something worth less.   But this however is a mistake because if black finds the right move he will wind up a pawn ahead.
?? This is the wrong move.  Best was 18...dxe5 in this position as black would be a pawn ahead.  As noted earlier with this move however white wins koki's Q for a N.
Now is a good time for black to take but he's still behind.  The question will he be able to come back?  That remains to be seen.

?? This capture however is also a blunder.  It looks like a very good move and in general appears worthy of a !.  But it's not a good idea to get attempted because it's well known that what looks good can be and sometimes is bad.  This is an example.  It looks like white won back a pawn however this move will allow black to win back the Q for a B and P after a discover a check on his next move.

I don't know why black played this maybe it was to put pressure on the e file.  However best was a R fork with the immediate 22...Re5! winning a free piece this time henceforth giving black the advantage.

! This is a good move because in general as per what Mr. Stockel told me while unlike with development and controlling the center there's no rush with this.  But it's a good idea to double up your rooks like this and what's good about this is that the doubled rooks are not on the same color.  Because Jack also said that it's not a good idea to bring your rooks on the same colored square.

! Good choice.  Black decides to avoid exchanging R's with this move.  I like it because in general when you're behind it's not a good idea to exchange as it would give you less to defend with in the endgame.

At first I wasn't sure why but quickly figured it out.  The idea behind this move is combine both rooks on one file.  Jack also mentioned that it's usually a good idea to do that because it's what makes doubled rooks powerful and dangerous against the opponent because they generally pose very serious threats that are not easy to deal with.
In my mind this move was pointless.  I believe that black was worried about a dangerous check with the E rook LSB and the remaining N.  But what he forgot is that his LSB defends against it.

In the meantime Gerhard has now united his R's as noted earlier.  And as it turns out they pose a very serious threat that black has to worry about.  And if he's not careful white will be able to mate him.

!! Very good choice which shows that black was thinking ahead.  Had he not seen this it would have been game over by exchanging R's with 26.R2e8+!! 26...Rxe8 27.Rxe8#  However black is not out of the woods and "he better be careful from now on".  Otherwise white will be able to force a win.
In the meantime white's not taking any chances either.  He knew that leaving his N on g5 would leave it en-prise and that black would win it after 26...PXN.

?? I don't know why black played this.  But this is his losing blunder.  Despite being behind best was to force an exchange with 26...Be4.  With this move however white will either win a free piece or find a mating pattern in which black will not be able to avoid this time.
Very smart choice.  White's intention is to force mate or win a free piece.  What doesn't realize is that koki could have done both.  How?

?? Now it's all over and there's no going back this time.  Yes he did protected his LSB by attacking white's R.  The idea was to gain tempii  Unfortunately for black however this move seals his fate.  That's because in the next few moves it will lead to an inevitable mating sequence.  It actually starts when white actually gains tempo with his next move.  So in short koki missed the real threat.
Black is trying to force an exchange but instead of allowing it white can now play the move that I talked about earlier.  And that's the move that seals black fate once and for all.
As I expected.  Yes it does prevent the loss of a R but no matter what black does white has a forced win.
The obvious response.
Forced.
He also could have played 31...g6 but didn't want to lose a pawn.  Even if he did that white would still mate quickly.
Forced.
Also forced.

!! This move protects his LSB.  But this time it's not just good it's extraordinarily brilliant worthy of two exclamation points as opposed to one.  And that's because white's LSB will be used as an extra piece to coordinate the mating pattern which is going to unfold soon.

Well given that white is going to mate black has nothing better to do then take.  The idea being is that no move is better then the other in this case.  Therefore I would've resigned at this point if I were black because of what's going to come on the next move.

Overall an instructive game with a lot for both players to learn.  The moral being and this is the same mistake that sometimes even GM's make.  But we learned that it's always important to be very careful where you place or your pieces.  In other words don't leave them en-prise as it can cause problems.  So I guess you can say to watch the entire board carefully or "be a spectator of your game".  Otherwise you might wind up paying the ultimate price as was the case here.

While this is meant to be an instructive game I have to say I made some mistakes that a player around my rating would have capitalized on. I managed to clean it up in the end and have to say my opponent gave a valiant effort.
The closed Sicilian. Not all that popular but I like using it from time to time. First used it by accident in an over the board event. (Did Bb5 instead of Bc4).
Alternative: Bd7. Either way is ok but at least you don't trap the bishop in using that approach.
Alternative: Bxd7+ Qxd7 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 e5. I didn't want to trade off my bishop just yet though.
? - e5 allows black to develop the bishop and castle. The longer this is delayed the harder it will be for black to develop.
I really should have taken with the queen here...
Protects the rook and attacks e4! a 2 to 1 advantage will win the pawn unless...
...I respond and protect it.
? - played without thinking about a b4! response
Finally! Was looking for this move for awhile.

Alternative: 11. ...b4! 12. Na2 a5 13. c3 Nc5 14. cxb4 axb4 15. Nxb4 Nxa4
But black plans to castle.
Simplifying the position and winning a pawn. Got to ask who really is benefitting from these exchanges though.
! - A necessary move. Any other response loses the queen
? - Ba6 saves the bishop as I plan to trade off an get rid of the attacker. My knight has done its job well.
Qd3 is also playable but with a simplified board I felt the need to apply pressure where I could.
I forgot why I played this move. Qd3 was considered here as well.
? - Allows for Qa5! making black think about trading queens.
Instead I choose to attack the knight and try and push for an endgame.
Alternative: Qd6! putting pressure on a weakened kingside due to so many key weapons being gone from the board
Qd3 serves well here as well.
? - Wasn't sure where black was going with the king but I felt that I needed to get it back to the exposed queenside in order to pursue victory.
?? - weakens my position quite a bit but I do expose more of the kingside. But now I'd like to ask how many of the higher rated players would make this sacrifice?
Keep the queen there for now and defend my weak pawns using my rook.
Be2 or Rd1 also protect the knight.
? - This move gave me an idea on how to expose the king.
Keeping pressure on it. Trying not to let it sit and get comfortable.
Nfd7 would've been a decent idea here.
?? - With this move I can deliver the finishing blows to the exposed king and attack the queen whose power has been greatly diminished in this game.
Collateral damage but his job was finished and he did it well.
I gave up a lot to get the position I wanted. Now an exposed king is closing in on a mating net.
A last gasp by black. Only delays the mate.
No need to take. Why give black more time to attack when the game is over?
A great effort on black's part. Despite my mistakes she hung in until the end and had some clever responses to some of my attacks.

After an interesting skirmish in the middle game featuring some inaccuracies on both sides this game wound down to a R+N v R ending. In researching the internet I found that the stronger side can rarely win but that the best move for both sides is sometimes far from obvious. So of course I was anxious to feed this into the GK analyzer (the only computer program I have available) to see if it could find better moves in the ending.
I have had less personal success with the common and more aggressive ... Bd6 which has the disadvantage of leaving Black's d pawn somewhat vulnerable.
Somewhat unexpected. I expected 10. cxd5 which seems to be more commonly played.

Hi everyone!

After conceding that Low Draw against Dan in that K & P ending in my return match against him I find myself in a rook ending a pawn up.  Dan ended up losing a pawn in the middlegame in order to beat off Old Matey who was loitering with intent on his kingside.  I found it really hard to make my advantage work and I had to watch out that Henry did not get stalemated on a8!  So did I get out of that one?  Well there is only one way to find out my friends READ ON!
1. .... e6 - the French Defense.
2...... d6 - unusual.  As Alice in Wonderland would say "Curiouser ......
3. ..... a6 - and curiouser!
4. ..... h6 - hmm maybe he is trying to take a leaf out of the Master Mater's book and play a few wacky openings and try and sucker me mid game!
5. ..... Nc6 - at last he develops a knight!
6. ..... Nge7 - and the other!
9. ..... Qxd5 - after this plethora of exchanges the Wicked Witch of the West occupies a strong central vantage point.  I will pull out all the stops to eject her from there!
11. Re1 - patience.
11. ...... Qd8 - aha a retreat!
13. Qc2 - waiting for King Dan to land on g8.

14. Rad1 - as Ion said in a previous match "Always put rook on same file as enemy queen no matter how many pieces are in the way".  It is amazing how many players can be hit by tactical shots this way.
16. Nxe5 - bishop trade.
18. Rd3 - I start to plan my mating attack.
19. Rg3 - with a rook lift.
21. Re4 - and another!
22. ..... Rf6 - organising his defense.
23. ..... cxd5 - B for N trade.
26. Qe2 - edging toward King Dan.
28. Nf3 - can't seem to find enough pieces for that killer blow.
30. Nb3 - I hit on plan B!
31. ...... bxc4 - Stage 1 queen trade .....

32. Nc5 - Stage 2 - one knight fork threatens another.  I am threatening either Nd7 forking the rooks on the f column and the black pawn on a6.  Dan defends with Be8 but abandons the pawn on a6.  The knight captures it and that poor little p(r)awn finds itself on Henry and Glenda's belated Valentine's Day menu!
35. Re3 - pressure on e6.
37. Rhf3 - defending f4.
38. a4 - I think it is time to push my outside passer.
39. a5 - onwards and upwards.
41. Rxg3 - rook trade.
43. Kf2 - Henry is heading towards the queenside to try and facilitate a tearful reunion with Glenda.
45. ..... Bc6 - at the moment Dan is scratching around.  Good. Meanwhile Henry keeps on heading east.
47. ...... Rf8 - now the black rook finally threatens to spoil Henry and Glenda's Valentine's Party.
48. ..... Kxd7 - now for a N for B trade.  Can Henry get to the a pawn in time?  We shall see!
51. Kxb3 - yes he can!
52. .... Kf7 - keeping guard over the g6 pawn.
53. a6 - just two squares away from Glendadom.
54. ..... Rb1 - Oh dear - Henry is confined to the a column - can he escape?  We shall see!
57. Ka7 - Henry takes refuge behind the passed pawn but he is well and truly ...... stoooock!
60. c4 - trying to open the c file to cut off King Dan from it!
61. Rxc4 - pawn trade.
64. Rxg6 - finally the g6 pawn falls and so does the rest of black's kingside.
66. Rxh5 - another p(r)awn for the table!
67. Rg5+ - now I have another passer this time on the h column.  This is gonna be mega useful.
68. h5 - yup Glenda is now threatening to appear on h8!
69. h6 - said the a6 pawn to the h6 pawn "I'll race ya!"
71. Kc7 - stops all checks - dead!
72. ..... Kf6 - with Henry shielded from rook checks along the 7th rank it is now curtains for Dan.

73. a7 - this move now prompts Dan to hit the resign button.  Dan will have to give up his rook for the pawn to stop Glenda making her appearance on a8.  However once the rook and the pawn have been traded off Henry will head towards the kingside to protect his rook and to allow Glenda to appear on h8 and proceed to m8.  That's all for now folks but I will be back!  Anyhow - have a nice evening everyone!  Bye for now - Joanne
It was only later that the strong continuation 5 B-KN5! was discovered.
Prepares ...P-Q4. White ought now to have played 9 P-K5 N-K1 10 B-KB4 securing an advantage in space.
More precise was 14... Q-B5! 15 P-QB3 QR-Q1. With the text move Black obtains only a minute advantage; for that very reason however its exploitation is extremely instructive.
Not 15... BxP immediately because of 16 QR-N1.
Black initiates maneuvers whose object is to reduce the mobility of the opposing pieces and deprive the Knight of operational bases.

Here we see a frequent feature of the working of the two Bishops: under their protection the King generally finds it easy to press towards the center; the enemy King on the other hand is kept back by their action.
If White now wishes to keep his Bishop in the center he must concede control of the Q file.
If White were to allow ...P-KB5 he would be completely hemmed in.
Threatens 28... P-R5 29 N-B1 P-R6 shattering White's Pawn formation.
Black has nearly immobilized the White Knight. White's position still seems solid but Black can use his Bishops to get rid of his opponent's only well-placed piece.
Threatening 32... BxB 33 PxB R-Q7 ch.
On 34 R-R1 34... K-K4 followed by P-B5 ch and Black's Rook will gain the seventh rank.
Even though White has an outside passed Pawn Black wins because of superior King position.
Not ...KxP?? 42 K-B4 winning.
White resigns as the Pawn will become a Queen.
I always use this opening. Of course though c5 may have been better.

Hi everyone!

This game started off as a Dutch Defense in a thematic mini-tournament.  This resulted in closed positional play right until the latter part of the middlegame where I managed to win a pawn and go into an endgame with a pawn up.  You would think this ought to have been a straightforward win wouldn't you?  Well not quite - let's throw some opposite coloured bishops into the mix and things were not as straightforward as they seemed even when I increased the advantage to that of two pawns the graffiti on my wall was reading "Low Draw".  However before hitting that Offer Draw button I decided to have one last throw of the dice but did it pay off?  Well in order to find out you will have to read on ......

1. ..... f5 - this is the Dutch Defense and I have had mixed results with this opening.  It looks as though I will be leaving Henry exposed on the Fool's Mate diagonal but in order for my opponent to plonk the Wicked Witch of the West on the h5 square it is not as simple as it first seems.
4. ..... g6 - this position is getting to be a little stonewallesque.  It sometimes leaves me really stuck for ideas and this is how I end up getting bogged down in the middle game.
6. ...... Bg7 - I complete the kingside fianchetto and the Fool's Mate diagonal is firmly closed off.
8. ..... Nf7 - not much happening.
9. ..... e5 - so I try and liven things up a little with a pawn break.
11. ...... Nxe5 - followed by a plethora of exchanges.
12. ...... 0-0 - finally Henry is tucked away on the kingside.
15. ..... b6 - even with those exchanges I seem to be in a defensive mode.
17. ...... Ne5 - I return my knight to its outpost.
19. ..... Rad8 - lining my rook on the same file as the Witch.
20. ..... Bxe5 - B for N exchange.  Nice to keep the bishop pair.

22. ..... Bf7 - one move ago white played the seemingly strong f4.  However this has left Roger with a backward e pawn and now I sneakily discover an attack on it.  Glenda is getting her broomstick ready ......
24. ..... Re6 - pile on.
25. ...... Bh6 - threatening Bxf4 as the e3 pawn is pinned to the Witch.
27. ..... Rf8 - I have a very subtle plan here to win that e3 pawn.  Where there's a will there's a way.
30. .... Bc8 - now I am threatening the rooks on the a6-f1 diagonal.
31. .... Ba6 - I play it anyway.
32. ..... Re8 - pile on renewed.

33. Qd2 - now I can start the exchanges which will alter the course of the game.  By taking off the knight on d3 I ensure I get the e3 pawn but the price I will pay is that I end up with opposite colour bishops.
36. Qd2 - there is a lull but there is one further set of exchanges to go.
37. Bd2 - the queens.
38. ..... Bxc3 - I take a pawn and end up with a material plus of two points but this is in no way a gimmie!
40. ..... Re6 - protecting the vulnerable c6 pawn but for how long?
41. ..... Kf7 - Henry marches to the c6 pawn's aid but alas he doesn't get very far.
44. Bd3 - Oh dear now my f5 pawn is vulnerable.
46. ..... d4 - protecting Fou Lenoir and blocking off the e file but I am still saddled with vulnerable pawns!
47. ..... Bc1 - my poor little f5 pawn is now a gonner.  However Fou Lenoir goes for the white queenside pawns.

50. fxe5 - now the rooks have been traded off and it really is an opposite colour bishop ending.  I decided to let the pawn on a7 go for the pawns on a3 and b4 and regain my two pawn advantage.  However it does allow white to get a passed pawn.  The alternative was to play a6 but then Roger could always play Be4 and then my queenside pawns could fall.  So I decided Bxa3 to be the lesser of the two evils.
51. .... Bxb4 - at least I have no less than FOUR passers on the queenside.  However will any of them reach Glendadom?  We shall see!
52. ..... a5 - I can only try.
54. Ke4 - centralising his king and going for the d5 pawn.  Fou Lenoir tries to protect it but finds himself on the next turn overloaded.
56. ..... Bxh6 - forced.
57. .... a3 - just two more squares.
58. ... Bg7 - my last throw of the dice - a pin!
60. Ke4?? - I think this is the loser.  Next move I play my winner - c5!
62. ..... c4 - the vital a2-g8 diagonal is now blocked.

63. .... Kxe6 - Henry snaps off Roger's final pawn and now three pawns down Roger decides to hit the resign button.  Here are his post game comments: "In my white game disregarding the computer analysis the move I thought lost it for me was #53. Instead of h5 I should have moved my K to Ke2. This would have stopped you B from guarding the diagonal including h6 for my advancing pawn. Of course being several pawns down was a killer in end game". He will not be able to stop Glenda from appearing on either c1 or a1.  That's all for now folks but I will be back with another endgame where I have had to deal with stubborn resistance in a rook ending from a Class C Player by the name of Dan.  Until then have a good read and a nice weekend - Kind regards - Joanne

Dutch - classical variation 

I initially was impressed with this opening but I have not liked the results. Perhaps I should study more master games with Be7 and d6 - I'm not optimistic however. There are several problems:

(1) The weakness on f4 - A solid strong loyal companion in both the Leningrad and Stonewall varaitions mr. f is virtually alone in the classical - protected only by mr. e whose job in the other two variations is shielding the king from diagonal checks. I can play Kh8 but it wastes time and doesn't solve the problem of being forced to take *out* of the center and open the e file (rather than the d file which is what the Dutch naturally prefers). Another option is using mr. g to protect it (like in the Leningrad) but if I play g6 I want to play Bg7!

(2) The e7 bishop is AWFUL - look at it! It lacks a legal move!! There's not a 'good' bishop and a 'bad' one (like there is in both other variations) there are TWO bad bishops...it's hard to figure out which one is worse!

At the end of the day this is the reason people don't play the Dutch - king safety problems a weak overextended mr. f and a cramped position that keeps your bishops home. You're grabbing space but doing nothing with it!

Leningrad and Stonewall have both made me proud - let's go back to them!

!
Hitting the aforementioned weak mr. f

*
(!) e5 is a famous hole in the Dutch defense - it's been the infiltration square for my position on numerous occasions and if my opponent can win this square (though the classical fights for it very effectively) they may also win the day.

(?) The queen is pointed at f5 the bishop is ready to jump into the attack on d3 and with the cluster of minors right next door mr. f's head would be on my opponent's wall in no time and if I'm not careful everything behind him will share that fate.
my bishop was terrible while his was strong so this is a good trade for both of us - my opponent liberates the knight I get equal value out of a loser bishop - yayyyyy

Hi everyone!

I have been trying to find a game to annotate which involved yours truly and a fellow Bigpeta Club member.  I think it may be best to fish out one of my games with Coach Ion which I did not get round to annotate.  Sadly it was not one of my best efforts against The Coach and indeed I was absolutely steamrollered!  However it does have some interest value because the guy who ran this mini-tournament was Freddy the Master Mater.  Freddy just lurves to play unusual openings and this is one of his experiments.  Anyhow this is the Traxler (Wilkes-Barre Opening) arising out of the Two Knights Defense.
3. ..... Nf6 - this is the Two Knights Defense.  Now comes the first wild move.
4. Ng5 - which hits out at f7 threatening a knight fork.
4. ..... Bc5 - of which black ignores.  Yee Ha - this is the Traxler - guys and dolls!
5. Nxf7 - fork.
6. Kf1 - if Henry takes the dsb then Nxe4+ is not pleasant.
8. Nxh8 - gobble gobble!
8. ...... Nd4 - in come the cavalry!
9. d6 - line opener for Fou Leblanc to enable the knight on h8 to extricate itself onto f7.
10. ..... d5 - but Ion cuts off this pipeline.
11. d3 - this opens lines for Fou Leblanc to get out but moresoever it creates a flight square for Glenda should Ion's lsb come to g4.
14. ..... Qh4+!! - Ssssss and double sssss! Here comes the Wicked Witch of the West and this is looking really nasty for Henry.
15. g3 - this does not cut the mustard.
17. .... Be2 - Ion does not take my rook.  This is a really horrible move as not only does it threaten a royal fork on f3 but Old Matey is threatening to descend onto f1.
18. Qe1 - stops Old Matey in his tracks but alas Glenda is a gonner.  Here commeth that Royal Fork!
20. Kxe1 - I still have a material advantage but not for long.
21. Rd8 - now Old Matey is threatening to descend on d1!
22. Nc3 - development at last but too little too late.  Now Ion sacs his rook!
24. Kd2 - Henry tries to run for the hills.  However .......

24. ...... c4+!! - Here I resigned on the grounds of Unavoidable Mate.  If PXP then Qe2 is mate.  Ion's Wargaming Project has certainly stood him in excellent stead to steamroller "She Who Wants to be TheBlackQueen!"  I hope you all have a good read.  Bye for now - Joanne

This game was part of "trachess's Leningrad Dutch" mini-tournament. The first 4 moves are predetermined to give us a staring position.

I wanted to annotate this game to show the resilience of my opponent and how it is possible to maintain a serious attack even after loosing material.

First 4 moves was preset by trachess's mini-tournament with Leningrad Dutch opening.
The game starts with move 5.
Mistake from karatekid opening the diagonal for my bishop. So I tell myself "That's all I need to win this game! ( or is it? )
I've got a 3 point piece advantage at this point but... his queen has taken control over my bishop for the long diagonal. And that positional advantage will disturb me until the endgame.
Only move possible to protect my Rook. ( Don't even think about e5 because : 9. dxe6 e.p. )
My next move will be a mistake but I want to prevent ... Bg7

Aie! I didn't see that coming. But It's part of Leningrad weakness for black (Ng5). I've learn from this mistake. The fact that my Bishop isn't there anymore and that the white Bishop is occupying h6 I couldn't do h6 as defencive move.
Now he's giving in real pressure on my King side.
The pawn I chose for the exchange here is crucial for future defense against his Queen diagonal. I need to keep my pawn on the e column.
This puts more pressure on his Queen diagonal. As you can see if he can clear the diagonal it's mate with Qg7.
Now you can see the importance of having my pawn to protect the diagonal.
Finally I feel the pressure going down a little and I got out of having my Knight pinned in front of my Queen by putting him in check.
His King is in a fragile position with his pawn on g missing.
More pressure! With this move he forces me to weaken my defense of the diagonal and he adds a pressure coming from his Rook.
I couldn't let him have the clear way for his Rook on the f column. But by advancing my pawn he regains access to the diagonal with his Queen.

Nice move! He gains my Knight because I can't take his Bishop back. If I do... :
21. ... Kxf6  22. Nxe4+  (double check). Wherever I place my King he comes in with his Queen at Qf6+ which puts me in a very uncomfortable position.
This is an attempt to regain control over the g7 and f6 square to prevent an attack from his Queen.
So would you say his Bishop is trapped? Let's see...
If I take his Bishop he can finally open the f column fxg5 and that would pin my Bishop against my King. I would also loose access to the g column for my Rook. And his pawn structure is solidified.
I can't take his bishop right now because of Qf6+. From there he can force a threefold draw.
Now that I'm occupying the g column with my Rook I can take the Bishop.
As you can see he can't really push his attack further now that I've placed my pieces at the right place.
I can see he tried to remove the pin on his Bishop. But this Finally gives me an opportunity to attack.
Rook sacrifice! (That move opens up the diagonal on his King) If he takes it I've got a mate sequence. If he doesn't take it he is sure to have some material loss.
He decides to take it. Mate in 5

Hi everyone!

Here is the first of two endgames from a new sparring partner called Dan.  He is a Class C player but with his stats - he has only lost 3 games out of 6 against me - he can start looking up towards Class B status.  I will now show you a couple of games against him in Chicoboy's Club's Mini-Tournament.  My score against him was 1.5 - 0.5 in my favour.  This is the game in which I was to concede a Low Draw in a K & P ending.  So how did this happen?  Well I end up trying out the Philidor Defense against him.  Surprisingly when I have played it I have done pretty well with it and one of those victories was my first ever Class A victory when I had a Class C rating - so I thought I would try it.  Here is how it all panned out.  Dan opens with 1. e4.
2. ..... d6 - this move is the Philidor Defense named after Andre Danican Philidor who first played this move in a serious tournament.  It's one drawback is that it shuts in Fou Lenoir.
3. h3 - unusual but playable.
4. ...... Be7 - development.
5. ...... 0-0 - Henry is tucked away on the kingside - now I need to sort out my queenside.
7. Nh2 - this curious move prepares Ng4.
9. ...... Bd7 - I did not want the Wicked Witch of the West to bear down on Henry on g4 so I decided to let Dan initiate the next set of trades.
11. .... Na6 - gotta get my pieces out somehow!
14. ...... Ne6 - putting the question to Dan's dsb.

17. ..... Qg5?! - Gameknot Analysis seemed to indicate that this was the move that condemned me to that Low Draw.  I really can't seem to resist the habit to trade queens.  Over the past few years I have managed to trust in Glenda a bit more but sometimes I do tend to lapse into those bad habits of inappropriate exchanges and passivitis!
22. ..... Rxf8 - after this plethora of exchanges Gameknot Analysis indicates the position as dead level.  Dan and I continue to trade.
24. Kxf1 - and it brings King Dan one step closer to centralisation.  I must now follow suit with Henry.
26. ..... Ke5 - Henry gets centralised first but a fat loada good it is gonna do - he will be driven off his perch as you will see.
28. ...... g5 - trying to keep King Dan out of f4 but Dan finds counterplay on the queenside.
32. ..... Kd6 - Henry must retreat.  He now tries to get at the queenside pawns but Dan finds a way of preventing this.
35. ..... b5 - I am the Desperate Dan here!  I am doing my best to break through but Dan finds the right move.
37. ..... h6 - the queenside is completely locked.  Can I try something on the kingside?  We shall see.

42. .... Kf6- I decided that there was no mileage out of h5 and the writing is now firmly on my Facebook Wall - LOW DRAW!  I take nothing away from Dan here in the entire 43 moves played he made NO ERRORS whatsoever and I made one inaccuracy - so Dan's performance is epic utterly epic although I was certainly loathe to concede 9 rating points Dan deserved every one of them.  So I ended up hitting the offer draw button and Dan accepted.  Thankfully in my return match things worked out much better for me but not without a fight.  That game will be annotated sometime this week.  Until then bye for now - Joanne
I've only recently stated exploring the Elephant Gambit.

I've never attempted a Two Bishop Mate before.
62. ... fxg4 would have made things easier for me.
I wanted to have a "pure" Two Bishops Mate with no other men on the board.
In retrospect I could have just promoted my third Pawn (to a Rook or Queen) and then forced White to take it.
I was completely willing to risk the easy mate I could have had by getting a Queen for a chance to attempt the Two Bishops.

I'm a little uneasy now as I'm not absolutely confident I'll be able to stop the f-Pawn.
I thought I might not have merely have thrown away a win but also any chance at a draw!
